Description. Specimens are globular or sub-spherical (up to 9.7 cm in diameter, holotype ;
Fig. 2
A), with some incrustations of calcareous substrate. Oscules rounded, up to 1 mm in diameter, although only few are visible. Surface optically smooth, but microhispid. Consistency firm, almost incompressible. Color of the holotype is unknown and the paratype (UFPEPOR 181 ) is orange alive, turning dark gray, almost black after fixation in ethanol, with a light interior.

